My understanding was that this was by design.  This makes generating parameter for multi-chassis systems much easier, and means the per-chassis tuning is far less problematic.

Hmm. If it was by design, to be normalized from 0.0 to 1.0, then it stacks really badly with the usage of integer, that's also fixed in this commit. It would always round down to 0, so it wouldn't work as expected.

If there's a multi-chassis system, then each chassis should be in its own thermal zone, right? The thermal zones are independent of each other, so there would be no need to normalize RPM between them.

> Hmm. If it was by design, to be normalized from 0.0 to 1.0, then it stacks really badly with the usage of integer, that's also fixed in this commit. It would always round down to 0, so it wouldn't work as expected.

I could be mistaken here, but I do recall a change where we modified all the math to operate on 0-1 (or 1-100) ranges, as it simplified multi-chassis.  We should tread carefully and try to avoid breaking stuff.

I will fully assert that I haven't read beyond the commit message of this, so the actual patch might be fine.

> 
> If there's a multi-chassis system, then each chassis should be in its own thermal zone, right? The thermal zones are independent of each other, so there would be no need to normalize RPM between them.

In this context, multi-chassis means "The same board COULD be installed in 2 different chassis, and each chassis has different fan characteristics that need to be detected at runtime"  It does not mean more than one node in a single chassis.

OK, thanks for the clarification. If the same board could be installed in two different chassis, then shouldn't thermal tuning be done for each chassis, and the parameters updated accordingly? If detected at runtime, D-Bus could be used to update the parameters accordingly, without having to do some strange special scaling here to compensate.

As for breaking stuff, it was broken before, and it's working now, so there's that. The RPM input is now correct, and the units in the PID loop now use RPM as intended.

> OK, thanks for the clarification. If the same board could be installed in two different chassis, then shouldn't thermal tuning be done for each chassis, and the parameters updated accordingly?

Not generally;  As a rule, the same per-thermal controller PID loops can be used chassis to chassis, with only the fan loops changing.  This assumes that fans have roughly linear responses to input, which while not true, is true enough for most servers that the integral components can compensate for it over time.  Doing this prevents having to retune every component for every chassis, which would rapidly go into exponential configurations that would need explicit tuning instead of just testing.


> If detected at runtime, D-Bus could be used to update the parameters accordingly, without having to do some strange special scaling here to compensate.

that's kind of what entity-manager does, it updates parameters dependent on hardware getting detected.  The key here is that the per-chassis parameters are separate from the non unique parameters so that EM can update the parameters separately, and we have a common cooling metric (0-100% cooling) that everything can standardize their tuning on.

> 
> As for breaking stuff, it was broken before, and it's working now, so there's that. The RPM input is now correct, and the units in the PID loop now use RPM as intended.

have the responses to the DBus APIs changed at all?  I kinda wonder if it was "broken" for json configs, but working for dbus configs.  With that said, again, I haven't read the content of the patch, so it very well could just be fixing stuff.
Good thoughts. I'm waking up this patch again, since it has been some time. Is the above still a concern?
Q: So is this new logic covered in a unit test anywhere?
There are already existing unit tests in the test/pid_fancontroller_unittest.cpp file. I did not add any new tests. No new logic was added here, just correcting the existing types and scaling.
Done
I would recommend pulling this change out since it's unrelated and is an easy patch to land as it has no behavioral changes.

Hmm, this is necessary here, to make a smooth transition between a 1-entry cache (scaled only) and a 2-entry cache (scaled and unscaled). It reduces the blast radius, versus making an equivalent change elsewhere.
Rebased to latest master. Updated name of _unscaled member (removed leading underscore).
This old patch rebased without incident.
Oh.. scaled RPM is actually PWM?
Nope, scaled RPM is between (0.0, 1.0) range based on a preconfigured min and max from somewhere, and unscaled RPM is the raw RPM value from the hardware.
Would it be easier to prevent this bug if we call this value as unscaledRPM instead?
Nope, see above.
Do we need unit test coverage for these?

There's already unit test coverage here. I just added getCachedValues() to zone_mock.hpp, as a wrapper function for getCachedValue(), to avoid breaking many existing tests. There's already many tests of inputProc() in the pid_fancontroller_unittest.cpp file.
Giving myself +2, as somebody else has already given +1
